Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours and be the fourth U.S. president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The award, medal and check of $1.4 million will be given to him, among other things, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and have a busy schedule.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who elected him in October from among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's planning then envisages an interview with Norway's King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will peak in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, but only the third to receive the award within the Committee.
The White House announced in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award ceremony.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he is aware that he is receiving this award by being a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.1 million).
He intends to donate it to charitable works, but he has not yet decided which ones.
His programme will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was quite reluctant at this price in the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, that he felt that he did not deserve it fully.
He also repeated several times that this is not a prize for himself alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As of the announcement, he said it would be an “invitation to action” for him.
