USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It even becomes comical, the hard work with which Barack Obama, president of the reputation of sage, reproduces his predecessor’s strategy on the Afghan question, which he considered himself to be quite simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine sweat, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the phrase "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, which is more, to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A new way forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a Iraq consumed by the civil war as being “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only possible and likely to be so successful that the newspapers at the moment do not talk about Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, it said, objectively speaking, he left his successor in a much more favorable final situation than one could have hoped.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him to increase the military contingent, including the Afghan Operation Commander, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the White House's reluctance despite subordination habits.
He asked 40,000 men to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months, but in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to fulfill the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted out of 10,000.
What brings the most problems in Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete this whole process within three years, and the entire Obama doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that an increase in half will bear the same fruit as progression in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is marked by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day according to what arranges them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will only remain the dust in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of various ethnic groups, given the lack of clarity on relations, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the founding of a “quick-to-action” state, which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The timeline of Obama’s strategy is perplexing by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out of reality heart can be convinced that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of the war for their "prompt return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it the indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that the Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is oriented towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their constituents how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor that can radically change the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the tightened sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult issue of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will lead to a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only rusty thing for Obama is that he has three years left until the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time for him to embark on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
