Czech discovery: a substance that works on "hardening" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the proliferation of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed an immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, takes the lead on the fact that the combination does not work as intensively on the common variants of the virus as well as some already available drugs.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, it is possible to radically prolong the life of patients through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption leads to a number of side effects.
In addition, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of the development of so-called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarbonates act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbonates are a combination of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way than all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings to virus proteins.
Metalocarbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A traitorous and resilient virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explained in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The effectiveness of this series of substances on the proteases of HIV has been tested in test specimens as well as on its resistant variants, obtained from HIV-infected patients.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metallocarbonates is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on resistant versions against which common drugs are often ineffective.
Metalocarbonates, with their unique mechanism of action and their other properties such as their biological and chemical stability, their low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications are therefore interesting combinations to examine further to go towards the development of biochemistry-effective drugs against HIV.
