A management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about having employees adhere to the "values" determined from above as they used to be by products, by imposing it on consumers.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors regularly returns!
Demobilization of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously jeopardizes the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IE "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that the revenues of authoritarian management are totally counterproductive.
That is why we are calling for a managerial revolution that would be to put employees at the center of the company’s concerns in the same way as the customer.
The Relative Usefulness of Internal Opinion Surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- Firstly, because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do priority... what it has always done. !
Secondly, because authoritarianism—one of the pathologies of power—grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, suggesting that it is possible to maneuver the " levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, engagement for the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a way to realize part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only the studies derived from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business based on a pre-determined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "on-the-spot".
In this way, they create a space for concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: ‘Just War’ Worth Praise to Obama’s Right
The U.S. right has welcomed the speech delivered in Oslo on Friday by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of “just war” against U.S. enemies.
