The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa findae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long for 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with falcon claws and it had a louver.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to have these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the emerging land of the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
In fact, he informs us about the ties of kinship, the distribution and the characteristics of these.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team tells us that they sometimes find a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique to a sedimentary layer dating back to the Trias.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named him Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete fragments of bones.
Not all experts in palaeontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he specifies that it confirms some theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify all the first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, when the Saurians divided themselves into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor appeared later and from which descend the birds, the sauropods and the herbaceous part of which the herp, the four-footed to the neck, and those which appear to them.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa was one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues to suggest that the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in its bones at the skull level, as did the birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also had airbags and a lightweight frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Saurians had appeared there.
Therefore, the three major lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all of the emerging lands that formed the Pangaea supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a palaeontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the Silesaurus, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group of dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved, while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of modern crocodiles and many other saurians.
