However, one who, awakened, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the influence of the drug.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design homes, paint paintings or write novels, but sometimes it encourages the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A conscious state of awakening, taking the form of a dream, can occur in the most diverse forms, at best it is called visions, at the worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
