About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenic crisis, the people concerned can no longer make the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper excitement, which makes them suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the consciousness is drowned under the sensations.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the door to a flood of ideas and fantasies coming from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at the CHU in Heidelberg (General Psychiatry in the Universitätsklinikum).
