75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for young women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fertility and Professional Career of Women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their careers limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the start of couple life and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment employed.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are repulsing entry into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 who have a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 for those who work in the public sector. "These data show that women who have a stable job needed more time in their lives to achieve it, and bringing them together again.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the start date of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child later.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who did elementary and graduate studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher level studies reverse this program and prioritize achieving a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of an exact child.”
