Michelin and Fesvial, kits for helmet wear
The tyre manufacturer Michelin, in collaboration with the Spanish Foundation for Road Safety (Fesvial), has launched a campaign to encourage wearing the helmet, mainly among young motorcyclists, as both structures have indicated today.
The aim of this initiative is to raise awareness of the importance of wearing the helmet, since it is the only protection element that prevents head injuries, or even death, in the event of a two-wheel accident.
Michelin said the campaign was part of its commitment to road safety, which goes “beyond the design and manufacture of ever safer products”, and stated that it was contributing to this goal through other educational and informational actions.
This new campaign to encourage the wearing of the helmet on two wheels, under the motto “To be or not to be”, will include a first phase during which posters will be distributed in more than 500 motorcycle garages, in order to ensure the widest dissemination.
Lastly, Michelin stressed that road safety “is a constant concern” for the company, because as a tyre manufacturer for two-wheeled vehicles, one of its main objectives is to develop ever safer products.
Sales of light commercial vehicles are on the rise
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market is starting to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decline, according to figures from the employer union of manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, that of dealers.
The good news should, however, be nuanced, since the reference for the comparison, November 2008, was particularly bad, with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite last month's rebound, the registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% below those in the previous fiscal year.
Since January, the addition of all vehicles that fall into the light commercial vehicle category (derived from passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, light vans and light trucks) has been 95,853.
The big clouds that affect their demand the most have not been dissipated. In fact, although they are also purchased by individuals, most of the purchases are made by small or medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100% of cases pay through external financing.
Thus, in addition to the constraints involved in limiting bank credits, other factors such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the poor economic conjuncture need to be added.
In the face of this situation and unlike passenger vehicles, aid for the 2000E has served little.
In addition to individuals, self-employed and SMEs wishing to acquire a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a level of CO2 emissions that does not exceed 160 grams per kilometre, it can also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
Yesterday, Ganvam reiterated the need for the administration to pay particular attention to these vehicles and also to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses).
The dealers' association expects a similar year 2010 to the year that ends, for which it calculates a 19% drop in sales (touring vehicles and 4x4).
Emergency braking assistance is now obligatory
As this has happened with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as it will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, through its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all their strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these types of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more significant with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injured persons would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting lightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he assists by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
